description.value: Terracotta cooking stove fragment.  A pot-support broken from a cooking-stove: a mask of Papposeilenos, much injured, the beard support lost, within a rectangular panel with obscure decoration across the top; the upper locks of hair divide in the centre and almost resemble horns. The back is decorated with a deep-sunk panel in which is a bust of a woman in high relief. Her hair is parted in the centre, with bunches high up on each side, falling in low-relief locks beside the neck. She is apparently clothed and may wear a choker necklace. The object has broken away from the rim of the fire-bowl.  The front and the back were each made in a one-piece mould and joined: a split between the two pieces is very noticeable in places. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with a thick black core and white inclusions. Traces of burning through use.

description.value: Part of a dark brown, plaited woven strap made of goat hair, incomplete at both ends. The strap is woven in regular twill weave producing a characteristic 'herringbone' appearance. Each element passes over two other elements then under two elements in an offset pattern (2/2 twill). There are eleven thread elements. Each thread element consists of 4 'z'-plied yarns twisted in 's'- direction. Several short strips of leather are present and are the remains of decorative stitching or of stitching used to strenghten the strap. Before conservation, January 2007.

description.value: Two goat hair strap fragments in final packaging – after conservation. Two fragments of a very dark brown, plaited strap made of goat hair. The first fragment is the total width of the strap.The plait consists of 15 warps lying side by side. Each warp strand is made of two 'z'-plied yarns 's'-twisted together. The first warp on the left edge is used as a weft, going over 2 warps then under one. When it reaches the right edge, it becomes a passive warp again. The second warp repeats the pattern as a weft, running over 2 warps then under one, until it becomes a passive warp again at the right edge. The sequence is repeated for the length of the strap and repeated when the first warp returns to the left edge. The pattern produces an uneven twill. The ends of the strap are not preserved.

description.value: Ebony stool: the finest surviving example of its type, this stool combines precious materials and successful design with superlative craftsmanship. The leather seat dips in a double cove to give contoured support to the body from any of its four sides. Ivory inlay imitating garlands of lotus petals adorns the upper portions of the legs, contrasting brightly with the rich, dark tone of the ebony. Below the lotus garlands are miniature squares of ivory imitating through joints. The supporting lattice bracing, composed of two inner vertical struts on each side, flanked by two angled struts, is also of ivory. Stretchers of ebony terminating in ivory ferrules, which fan out in imitation of a papyrus umbel, hold the legs firmly in place. The legs taper toward the bottom and then flare out again to form a delicate, aesthetically balanced support. Incised rings ornament the tapered half.Blue glazed composition goblet in the form of a lotus flower. Three-legged wooden table; painted representation of Renenutet before offering-table and column of Hieroglyphic text on top. Acacia wood chair; back inlaid with strips of ebony and ivory flowers and points; seat of woven string; lion-paw feet. Pottery jar with cover; cream slip; painted bands of blue lotus-petal decoration; Hieroglyphic text on the shoulder. Sandal made of wood with leather strap. Sandal made of wood with leather strap.
